Definition 3.1. The factorization category $\mathcal{F}\mathbf{C}$ of a small category $\mathbf{C}$ has objects: morphisms in $\mathbf{C}$, morphisms: $(h,k)\colon f\rightarrow g$ are pairs of morphisms in $\mathbf{C}$ such that $kfh=g$, that is commutative diagrams in $\mathbf{C}$ $\xymatrix{\bullet\ar[r]^{k}&\bullet\\ \bullet\ar[u]^{f}&\bullet\ar[u]_{g}\ar[l]^{h}}$ and composition is defined by $(h^{\prime},k^{\prime})(h,k)=(hh^{\prime},k^{\prime}k)$.
Definition 4.1. Recall from [2] that a natural system on $\mathbf{C}$ is a functor $D\colon\mathcal{F}\mathbf{C}\rightarrow\mathrm{\mathbf{Ab}}$. The Baues-Wirsching complex $F^{*}(\mathbf{C},D)$ of a small category $\mathbf{C}$ with coefficients in a natural system $D$ on $\mathbf{C}$ is a cochain complex of abelian groups concentrated in non-negative dimensions. In dimension $n$ this complex is given by the following product indexed by all sequences of morphisms of length $n-1$ in $\mathbf{C}$ $F^{n}(\mathbf{C},D)=\prod_{\bullet\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\sigma_{1}}}{{% \leftarrow}}\cdots\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\sigma_{n}}}{{\leftarrow}}\bullet}D(% \sigma_{1}\cdots\sigma_{n}).$ In this formula we assume that a sequence of length $0$ is an object $X$ in $\mathbf{C}$ which we also identify with the identity morphism $1_{X}$. The coordinate of $c\in F^{n}(\mathbf{C},D)$ in $\bullet\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\sigma_{1}}}{{\leftarrow}}\cdots\stackrel{{% \scriptstyle\sigma_{n}}}{{\leftarrow}}\bullet$ will be denoted by $c(\sigma_{1},\dots,\sigma_{n})$. The differential $d$ is defined as $\displaystyle d(c)(\sigma_{1},\dots,\sigma_{n+1})$ $\displaystyle=$ $\displaystyle D(1,\sigma_{1})c(\sigma_{2},\dots,\sigma_{n+1})$ $\displaystyle+\sum_{i=1}^{n}(-1)^{i}c(\sigma_{1},\dots,\sigma_{i}\sigma_{i+1},% \dots,\sigma_{n+1})$ $\displaystyle+(-1)^{n+1}D(\sigma_{n+1},1)c(\sigma_{1},\dots,\sigma_{n}).$ over an $n$-cochain $c$ for $n\geq 1$, and $d(c)(\sigma)=D(1,\sigma)c(X)-D(\sigma,1)c(Y)$ for $n=0$ and $\sigma\colon X\rightarrow Y$. The cohomology of $\mathbf{C}$ with coefficients in $D$ is the cohomology of the complex $F^{*}(\mathbf{C},D)$, it is denoted by $H^{*}(\mathbf{C},D)$.
Definition 6.8. A colocalization is an adjoint pair ($\varphi$ right adjoint to $\psi$) $\xymatrix{\mathbf{C}\ar@<.5ex>[r]^{\varphi}&\mathbf{D}\ar@<.5ex>[l]^{\psi}}$ such that $\varphi\psi=1_{\mathbf{D}}$ and the unit is the identity natural transformation.
Definition 6.1. A localization is an adjoint pair ($\varphi$ left adjoint to $\psi$) $\xymatrix{\mathbf{C}\ar@<.5ex>[r]^{\varphi}&\mathbf{D}\ar@<.5ex>[l]^{\psi}}$ such that $\varphi\psi=1_{\mathbf{D}}$ and the counit is the identity natural transformation.
Definition 3.8. Let $(E,F)$ an exceptional pair. We define objects $\mathcal{L}_{E}F$ and $\mathcal{R}_{F}E$ (which we call left mutation and right mutation respectively) with the aid of distinguished triangles $\mathcal{L}_{E}F\rightarrow\mathop{\rm Hom\,}\nolimits^{\bullet}(E,F)\otimes E% \rightarrow F,$ $E\rightarrow\mathop{\rm Hom\,}\nolimits^{\bullet}(E,F)^{*}\otimes F\rightarrow% \mathcal{R}_{F}E,$ where $V[k]\otimes E$ (with $V$ vector space) denotes an object isomorphic to the direct sum of $\mathop{\rm dim\,}\nolimits V$ copies of the object $E[k]$. Note that under duality of vector spaces the grading changes sign.
Definition 3.2. Let $I$ be a two-sided ideal contained in the ideal of paths of length at least two of the path-algebra of a quiver $Q$. We call the pair $(Q,I)$ a quiver with relations (sometimes, with abuse of notation, we will forget the ideal $I$). The path-algebra of a quiver with relations is the algebra $\mathbb{C}Q/I$.
Definition 2.1. A stability condition $\sigma=(Z,\mathcal{P})$ on $\bf T$ consists of a group homomorphism $Z:K(\bf T)\rightarrow\mathbb{C}$, called the central charge, and strongly full, additive subcategories $\mathcal{P}(\phi){\,\subseteq\,}\bf T$, $\phi\in\mathbb{R}$. They keep the following compatibilities: (1) for any nonzero object $E\in\mathcal{P}(\phi)$, $Z(E)/|Z(E)|=\exp(i\pi\phi)$; (2) $\forall\phi\in\mathbb{R}$, $\mathcal{P}(\phi+1)=\mathcal{P}(\phi)[1]$; (3) if $\phi_{1}>\phi_{2}$ and $A_{j}\in\mathcal{P}(\phi_{j})$, $j=1,2$, then $\mathop{\rm Hom\,}\nolimits_{\bf T}(A_{1},A_{2})=0$; (4) for any nonzero object $E\in\bf T$ there is a finite sequence of real numbers $\phi_{1}>...>\phi_{n}$ and a collection of triangles $E_{j-1}\rightarrow E_{j}\rightarrow A_{j}$ with $A_{j}\in\mathcal{P}(\phi_{j})$, for all $j$, $E_{0}=0$ and $E_{n}=E$.
Definition 3.7. (i) An object $E\in\bf T$ is called exceptional if it satisfies $\displaystyle\mathop{\rm Hom\,}\nolimits^{i}$ $\displaystyle(E,E)=0,\qquad{\text{for}}\ i\neq 0,$ $\displaystyle\mathop{\rm Hom\,}\nolimits^{0}$ $\displaystyle(E,E)=\mathbb{C}.$ (ii) An ordered collection of exceptional objects $\left\{E_{0},\ldots,E_{n}\right\}$ is called exceptional in $\bf T$ if it satisfies $\mathop{\rm Hom\,}\nolimits^{\bullet}(E_{i},E_{j})=0,\qquad{\text{for}}\ i>j.$ We call an exceptional collection of two objects an exceptional pair.
Definition 3.10. Let $\mathcal{E}=\mbox{$\left\{E_{0},\ldots,E_{n}\right\}$}$ be an exceptional collection. We call $\mathcal{E}$ * strong, if $\mathop{\rm Hom\,}\nolimits^{k}(E_{i},E_{j})=0$ for all $i$ and $j$, with $k\neq 0$; * Ext, if $\mathop{\rm Hom\,}\nolimits^{\leq 0}(E_{i},E_{j})=0$ for all $i\neq j$; * regular, if $\mathop{\rm Hom\,}\nolimits^{k}(E_{i},E_{j})\neq 0$ for at most one $k\geq 0$, for all $i$ and $j$; * orthogonal, if $\mathop{\rm Hom\,}\nolimits^{k}(E_{i},E_{j})=0$ for all $i\neq j$ and $k$; * complete, if $\mathcal{E}$ generates $\bf T$ by shifts and extensions.
Definition 3.3. [Gau01a] The globular simplicial nerve $\mathcal{N}^{gl}$ is the functor from $\omega Cat_{1}$ to $Sets^{\Delta^{op}}_{+}$ defined by $\mathcal{N}^{gl}_{n}(\mathcal{C}):=\omega Cat(\Delta^{n},\mathbb{P}\mathcal{C})$ for $n\geq 0$ and with $\mathcal{N}^{gl}_{-1}(\mathcal{C}):=\mathcal{C}_{0}\times\mathcal{C}_{0}$, and endowed with the augmentation map $\partial_{-1}$ from $\mathcal{N}^{gl}_{0}(\mathcal{C})=\mathcal{C}_{1}$ to $\mathcal{N}^{gl}_{-1}(\mathcal{C})=\mathcal{C}_{0}\times\mathcal{C}_{0}$ defined by $\partial_{-1}x:=(s_{0}x,t_{0}x)$.
Definition B.2. Let $Y$ be a topological space. The singular simplicial nerve of $Y$ is the simplicial set $S_{*}(XY)$ defined as follows : $S_{n}(Y):={\mathbf{Top}}(\Delta^{n},Y)$ with $\partial_{i}(f)(t_{0},\dots,t_{n-1})=f(t_{0},\dots,t_{i-1},\dots,t_{n-1})$ and $\epsilon_{i}(f)(t_{0},\dots,t_{n+1})=f(t_{0},\dots,t_{i-1},t_{i}+t_{i+1},t_{i+% 2},\dots,t_{n+1})$.
Definition C.3. Let $\mathcal{C}$ be an $\omega$-category. Then the graded set $\omega Cat(\Delta^{*},\mathcal{C})$ is naturally endowed with a structure of simplicial sets. It is called the simplicial nerve of $\mathcal{C}$.
Definition 3.7. [Gau01a] The globular simplicial nerve $\mathcal{N}^{gl}$ is the functor from ${\mathbf{glCW}}$ to $Sets^{\Delta^{op}}_{+}$ defined by $\mathcal{N}^{gl}_{n}(X):=S_{n}(\mathbb{P}X)$ for $n\geq 0$ where $S_{*}$ is the singular simplicial nerve (cf. Appendix B) with $\mathcal{N}^{gl}_{-1}(X):=X^{0}\times X^{0}$, and endowed with the augmentation map $\partial_{-1}$ from $\mathcal{N}^{gl}_{0}(X)=\mathbb{P}X$ to $\mathcal{N}^{gl}_{-1}(X)=X^{0}\times X^{0}$ defined by $\partial_{-1}\gamma:=(\gamma(0),\gamma(1))$.
Definition E.1. Let $\mathcal{C}$ be a category (not necessarily small). Let $S$ be a collection of morphisms of $\mathcal{C}$. Consider the following universal problem : “There exists a pair $(\mathcal{D},\mu)$ such that $\mu$ is a functor from $\mathcal{C}$ to $\mathcal{D}$ and such that for any $s\in S$, $\mu(s)$ is an invertible morphism of $\mathcal{D}$.” Then the solution $(\mathcal{C}[S^{-1}],Q)$, if there exists, is called the localization of $\mathcal{C}$ with respect to $S$.
Definition 3.5. Let $X$ be a globular CW-complex. Then the path space of $X$ is the disjoint union $\mathbb{P}X=\bigsqcup_{(\alpha,\beta)\in X^{0}\times X^{0}}(X,\alpha,\beta)^{\bot}$ endowed with the disjoint union topology.
Definition C.1. [BH81b] [KP97] A precubical set consists of a family of sets $(K_{n})_{n\geqslant 0}$ and of a family of face maps $\xymatrix@1{{K_{n}}\ar@{->}[r]^{\partial_{i}^{\alpha}}&{K_{n-1}}}$ for $\alpha\in\{-,+\}$ which satisfies the following axiom (called sometime the cube axiom) : $\partial_{i}^{\alpha}\partial_{j}^{\beta}=\partial_{j-1}^{\beta}\partial_{i}^{\alpha}$ for all $i<j\leqslant n$ and $\alpha,\beta\in\{-,+\}$.
Definition 3.1. Let $\mathcal{C}$ be a non-contracting $\omega$-category. Denote by $\mathcal{R}^{-}$ (resp. $\mathcal{R}^{+}$) the reflexive symmetric and transitive closure of $\{(x,x*_{0}y),x,y,x*_{0}y\in\mathbb{P}\mathcal{C}\}$ (resp. $\{(y,x*_{0}y),x,y,x*_{0}y\in\mathbb{P}\mathcal{C}\}$) in $\mathbb{P}\mathcal{C}\times\mathbb{P}\mathcal{C}$.
Definition 5.1. The category ${\mathbf{Ho}}({\mathbf{glCW}})$ is called the category of dihomotopy types.
Definition 2.3. [GG01] The category ${\mathbf{glCW}}$ of globular CW-complexes is the category having as objects the globular CW-complexes and as morphisms the continuous maps $f:X\longrightarrow Y$ satisfying the two following properties : • $f(X^{0})\subset Y^{0}$ • for every non-constant execution path $\phi$ of $X$, $f\circ\phi$ must not only be an execution path ($f$ must preserve partial order), but also $f\circ\phi$ must be non-constant as well : we say that $f$ must be non-contracting.
Definition 3.6. Let $X$ be a globular CW-complex. Then the negative semi-path space $\mathbb{P}^{-}X$ (resp. positive semi-path space $\mathbb{P}^{+}X$) of $X$ are defined by $\displaystyle\mathbb{P}^{-}X=\bigsqcup_{\alpha\in X^{0}}(X,\alpha)^{\bot^{-}}$ $\displaystyle\mathbb{P}^{+}X=\bigsqcup_{\beta\in X^{0}}(X,\beta)^{\bot^{+}}$ endowed with the disjoint union topology.
Definition C.2. [BH81a, Str87, Ste91] An $\omega$-category is a set $A$ endowed with two families of maps $(s_{n}=d_{n}^{-})_{n\geqslant 0}$ and $(t_{n}=d_{n}^{+})_{n\geqslant 0}$ from $A$ to $A$ and with a family of partially defined 2-ary operations $(*_{n})_{n\geqslant 0}$ where for any $n\geqslant 0$, $*_{n}$ is a map from $\{(a,b)\in A\times A,t_{n}(a)=s_{n}(b)\}$ to $A$ ($(a,b)$ being carried over $a*_{n}b$) which satisfies the following axioms for all $\alpha$ and $\beta$ in $\{-,+\}$ : 1. $d_{m}^{\beta}d_{n}^{\alpha}x=\left\{\begin{CD}d_{m}^{\beta}x\hbox{ if $m<n$}\\ d_{n}^{\alpha}x\hbox{ if $m\geqslant n$}\end{CD}\right.$ 2. $s_{n}x*_{n}x=x*_{n}t_{n}x=x$ 3. if $x*_{n}y$ is well-defined, then $s_{n}(x*_{n}y)=s_{n}x$, $t_{n}(x*_{n}y)=t_{n}y$ and for $m\neq n$, $d_{m}^{\alpha}(x*_{n}y)=d_{m}^{\alpha}x*_{n}d_{m}^{\alpha}y$ 4. as soon as the two members of the following equality exist, then $(x*_{n}y)*_{n}z=x*_{n}(y*_{n}z)$ 5. if $m\neq n$ and if the two members of the equality make sense, then $(x*_{n}y)*_{m}(z*_{n}w)=(x*_{m}z)*_{n}(y*_{m}w)$ 6. for any $x$ in $A$, there exists a natural number $n$ such that $s_{n}x=t_{n}x=x$ (the smallest of these numbers is called the dimension of $x$ and is denoted by $dim(x)$).
Definition 3.2. The $\omega$-category $\mathbb{P}^{-}\mathcal{C}$ (resp. $\mathbb{P}^{+}\mathcal{C}$) is called the negative (resp. positive) semi-path $\omega$-category of $\mathcal{C}$.
Definition B.1. A simplicial set $A_{*}$ is a family $(A_{n})_{n\geq 0}$ together with face maps $\partial_{i}:A_{n}\rightarrow A_{n-1}$ and $\epsilon_{i}:A_{n}\rightarrow A_{n+1}$ for $i=0,\dots,n$ which satisfy the following identities : $\displaystyle\partial_{i}\partial_{j}=\partial_{j-1}\partial_{i}$ $\displaystyle\hbox{ if }i<j$ $\displaystyle\epsilon_{i}\epsilon_{j}=\epsilon_{j+1}\epsilon_{i}$ $\displaystyle\hbox{ if }i\leq j$ $\displaystyle\partial_{i}\epsilon_{j}=\left\{\begin{array}[]{c}\epsilon_{j-1}% \partial_{i}\\ \hbox{Identity}\\ \epsilon_{j}\partial_{i-1}\end{array}\right.$ $\displaystyle\begin{array}[]{l}\hbox{ if }i<j\\ \hbox{ if }i=j\hbox{ or }i=j+1\\ \hbox{ if }i>j+1\end{array}$ A morphism of simplicial sets from $A_{*}$ to $B_{*}$ consists of a set map from $A_{n}$ to $B_{n}$ for each $n\geq 0$ commuting with all operators defined on both sides. The category of simplicial sets is denoted by $Sets^{\Delta^{op}}$.
Definition 2.1. [Gau01a] An $\omega$-category $\mathcal{C}$ is non-contracting if $s_{1}x$ and $t_{1}x$ are $1$-dimensional as soon as $x$ is not $0$-dimensional. Let $f$ be an $\omega$-functor from $\mathcal{C}$ to $\mathcal{D}$. The morphism $f$ is non-contracting if for any $1$-dimensional $x\in\mathcal{C}$, the morphism $f(x)$ is a $1$-dimensional morphism of $\mathcal{D}$. The category of non-contracting $\omega$-categories with the non-contracting $\omega$-functors is denoted by $\omega Cat_{1}$.
Definition 3.8. Let $X$ be a globular CW-complex. Then set $\mathcal{N}^{gl^{-}}_{n}(X):=S_{n}(\mathbb{P}^{-}X)$ for $n\geq 0$ and $\mathcal{N}^{gl^{-}}_{-1}(X):=X^{0}$ with $\partial_{-1}(\gamma):=\gamma(0)$. Then $\mathcal{N}^{gl^{-}}$ induces a functor from ${\mathbf{glCW}}$ to $Sets^{\Delta^{op}}_{+}$ which is called the branching semi-globular nerve of $X$ .
Definition 2.2. Let $X$ be a globular CW-complex. A point $\alpha$ of $X^{0}$ is initial (resp. final) if for any execution path $\phi$ such that $\phi(1)=\alpha$ (resp. $\phi(0)=\alpha$), then $\phi$ is the constant path $\alpha$.
Definition B.3. [Dus75] An augmented simplicial set is a simplicial set $((X_{n})_{n\geq 0},(\partial_{i}:X_{n+1}\longrightarrow X_{n})_{0\leq i\leq n+% 1},(\epsilon_{i}:X_{n}\longrightarrow X_{n+1})_{0\leq i\leq n})$ together with an additional set $X_{-1}$ and an additional map $\partial_{-1}$ from $X_{0}$ to $X_{-1}$ such that $\partial_{-1}\partial_{0}=\partial_{-1}\partial_{1}$. A morphism of augmented simplicial set is a map of $\mathbb{N}$-graded sets which commutes with all face and degeneracy maps. We denote by $Sets^{\Delta^{op}}_{+}$ the category of augmented simplicial sets.
Definition 3.4. Let $\mathcal{C}$ be a non-contracting $\omega$-category. Then set $\mathcal{N}^{gl^{-}}_{n}(\mathcal{C}):=\omega Cat(\Delta^{n},\mathbb{P}^{-}% \mathcal{C})$ and $\mathcal{N}^{gl^{-}}_{-1}(\mathcal{C}):=\mathcal{C}_{0}$ with $\partial_{-1}(x):=s_{0}x$. Then $\mathcal{N}^{gl^{-}}$ induces a functor from $\omega Cat_{1}$ to $Sets^{\Delta^{op}}_{+}$ which is called the negative semi-globular nerve or ( branching semi-globular homology) of $\mathcal{C}$ .
Definition 3 (Example: CPTP maps). The symmetric monoidal category $\mathbf{CPTP}$ of completely positive trace preserving maps is defined as follows. The objects are natural numbers, with $n$ to be thought of as the space $M_{\_}n=\mathbb{C}^{n^{2}}$ of $n\times n$ complex matrices, that is, as the algebra of operators on the $n$-dimensional Hilbert space. The morphisms $m\to n$ are linear maps $M_{\_}m\to M_{\_}n$ that are completely positive and trace preserving. The idea is that these are the maps that preserve density matrices even when coupled with an ancilla. To formulate a formal definition, first note that $M_{\_}{mn}$ is the tensor product of Hilbert spaces $M_{\_}m$ and $M_{\_}n$, and so we can combine any linear maps $f:M_{\_}m\to M_{\_}n$, $g:M_{\_}{m^{\prime}}\to M_{\_}{n^{\prime}}$ into a linear map $f\otimes g:M_{\_}{mm^{\prime}}\to M_{\_}{nn^{\prime}}$. A linear map $f:M_{\_}m\to M_{\_}n$ is positive if $f(\rho)$ is a positive operator whenever $\rho$ is a positive operator ($v^{\top}\rho v\geq 0$ for all $v\in\mathbb{C}^{m}$). The map $f:M_{\_}m\to M_{\_}n$ is completely positive if for every natural number $p$ the linear map $(f\otimes p):M_{\_}{mp}\to M_{\_}{np}$ is positive. Categorical composition in $\mathbf{CPTP}$ is composition of linear maps. The monoidal structure is again given by multiplication $(m\otimes n\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\mathrm{def}}}{{=}}mn)$ on objects and on morphisms by the tensor product of linear maps. In the literature, CPTP maps are sometimes called ‘quantum channels’ or ‘superoperators’.
Definition 10 ([25], §3). The category $\mathbf{Tennent}$ has objects natural numbers, and morphisms $m\to n$ are pairs $(Q,f)$ where $Q$ is an equivalence relation on $m$ and $f\colon m\to n$ is a function that is injective on each $Q$-equivalence class: if $f(i)=f(i^{\prime})$ and $Q(i,i^{\prime})$ then $i=i^{\prime}$. The identity morphism $m\to m$ is $(m\times m,\mathrm{id}_{\_}m)$, where $(m\times m)$ is the universal equivalence relation. The composite $(R,g)\cdot(Q,f)$ is $(S,gf)$, where $S(i,i^{\prime})$ iff $Q(i,i^{\prime})$ and $R(f(i),f(i^{\prime}))$.
Definition 14. The symmetric monoidal category $\mathbf{CPTP_{\_}2}$ has objects natural numbers and morphisms $m\to n$ are CPTP maps $f:\mathcal{M}_{\_}{2^{m}}\to\mathcal{M}_{\_}{2^{n}}$. The monoidal structure is given similarly on objects by addition and on morphisms by tensor product. Thus it is a full monoidal subcategory of $\mathbf{CPTP}$.
Definition 8. The symmetric monoidal category $\mathbf{Injection}$ has objects natural numbers, considered as sets, and morphisms injections between them. Composition is composition of functions. The monoidal structure is multiplication on objects, and the pairing of injections on morphisms.
Definition 13. The symmetric monoidal category $\mathbf{Isometry_{\_}2}$ has objects natural numbers and morphisms $m\to n$ are isometries $f:\mathbb{C}^{2^{m}}\to\mathbb{C}^{2^{n}}$. The monoidal structure is given on objects by addition (NB $2^{n}2^{m}=2^{n+m}$) and on morphisms by tensor product of linear maps. Thus it is a full monoidal subcategory of $\mathbf{Isometry}$.
Definition 4 (Symmetric monoidal functor). If $\mathbf{C}$ and $\mathbf{D}$ are symmetric monoidal categories, then a strict symmetric monoidal functor is a functor $F:\mathbf{C}\to\mathbf{D}$ such that $F(I_{\_}\mathbf{C})=I_{\_}\mathbf{D}$, $F(A\otimes_{\_}\mathbf{C}B)=(F(A))\otimes_{\_}{\mathbf{D}}(F(B))$, and similarly with morphisms, and such that $F(\sigma_{\_}\mathbf{C})=\sigma_{\_}\mathbf{D}$. If $V:m\to n$ is an isometry then the mapping $\rho\mapsto V\rho V^{*}$ is a completely positive trace preserving map $m\to n$. This extends to an identity on objects functor $E:\mathbf{Isometry}\to\mathbf{CPTP}$.
Definition 1. A strict monoidal category is a category $\mathbf{C}$ together with a functor $\otimes:\mathbf{C}\times\mathbf{C}\to\mathbf{C}$ and an object $I$ such that $(A\otimes B)\otimes C=A\otimes(B\otimes C)$, $A\otimes I=I\otimes A=A$, $(f\otimes g)\otimes h=f\otimes(g\otimes h)$, and $f\otimes\mathrm{id}_{\_}I=\mathrm{id}_{\_}I\otimes f=f$. A symmetric strict monoidal category additionally has a natural isomorphism $\sigma_{\_}{A,B}:A\otimes B\cong B\otimes A$ such that $\sigma_{\_}{B,A}\sigma_{\_}{A,B}=\mathrm{id}_{\_}{A\otimes B}$ and $\tikzcd A\otimes B\otimes C\ar[d,"\sigma_{\_}{A,B}\otimes C"^{\prime}]\ar[dr,"% \sigma_{\_}{A,B\otimes C}"]\\ B\otimes A\otimes C\ar[r,"B\otimes\sigma_{\_}{A,C}"^{\prime}]&B\otimes C\otimes A$
Definition 2 (Example: Isometries). The symmetric monoidal category $\mathbf{Isometry}$ of isometries is defined as follows. The objects are natural numbers, with $n$ to be thought of as the Hilbert space $\mathbb{C}^{n}$. The morphisms $m\to n$ are linear maps $f\colon\mathbb{C}^{m}\to\mathbb{C}^{n}$ that are isometries $(||f(v)||=||v||)$. Categorical composition is just composition of linear maps. The monoidal structure is given on objects by multiplication: $m\otimes n\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\mathrm{def}}}{{=}}mn$. Note that the Hilbert space $\mathbb{C}^{mn}$ is the tensor product of $\mathbb{C}^{m}$ and $\mathbb{C}^{n}$, and so we can define the monoidal structure on morphisms by taking the usual tensor product of linear maps. More concretely, every isometry is represented by a matrix $V\in\mathbb{C}^{mn}$ such that $V^{*}V=\mathrm{I}$. Categorical composition is by matrix multiplication. The monoidal structure on morphisms is the Kronecker product.
Definition Let $\mathbb{A}$ be a small category. A functor $X:\mathbb{A}\rTo\linebreak[0]\mathbf{Set}$ is nondegenerate if the functor $-\otimes X:[\mathbb{A}^{\mathrm{op}},\mathbf{Set}]\rTo\linebreak[0]\mathbf{Set}$ preserves finite connected limits. Write $[\mathbb{A},\mathbf{Set}]_{\mathrm{nondegen}}$ for the category of nondegenerate functors $\mathbb{A}\rTo\linebreak[0]\mathbf{Set}$ and natural transformations between them.
Definition A self-similarity system is a small category $\mathbb{A}$ together with a functor $M:\mathbb{A}^{\mathrm{op}}\times\mathbb{A}\rTo\linebreak[0]\mathbf{Set}$ such that a. for each $a\in\mathbb{A}$, the set $\coprod_{c,b\in\mathbb{A}}\mathbb{A}(c,b)\times M(b,a)$ is finite b. (a condition to be described later).
Definition 2.1. A right module over a small $K$-linear category $\mathcal{D}$ is a $K$-linear functor $\mathcal{D}^{op}\longrightarrow Vect_{K}$, where $Vect_{K}$ denotes the category of $K$-vector spaces. Similarly, a left module over $\mathcal{D}$ is a $K$-linear functor $\mathcal{D}\longrightarrow Vect_{K}$. The category of all right (resp. left) modules over $\mathcal{D}$ will be denoted by $Mod$-$\mathcal{D}$ (resp. $\mathcal{D}$-$Mod$).
Definition 2.7. Let $\mathcal{D}$ be a small preadditive category and let $\mathcal{M}$ be a right $\mathcal{D}$-module. For each $m\in el(\mathcal{M})$, we consider the corresponding morphism $\eta_{m}:{\bf h}_{|m|}\longrightarrow\mathcal{M}$. A family of elements $\{m_{i}\in el(\mathcal{M})\}_{i\in I}$ is said to be a generating set for $\mathcal{M}$ if the induced morphism $\eta:\bigoplus_{i\in I}{\bf h}_{|m_{i}|}\longrightarrow\mathcal{M}~{}~{}~{}~{}% ~{}~{}~{}~{}~{}~{}(0,...,0,id_{|m_{i}|},0,...,0)\mapsto m_{i}$ is an epimorphism in $Mod\text{-}\mathcal{D}$. In other words, every element $m\in el(\mathcal{M})$ may be expressed as a sum $m=\sum_{i\in I}\mathcal{M}(f_{i})(m_{i})$, where each $f_{i}\in Hom_{\mathcal{D}}(|m|,|m_{i}|)$ and all but finitely many $\{f_{i}\}_{i\in I}$ are zero.
Definition 2.2. Let $\mathcal{M}$ be a right $\mathcal{D}$-module with a given right $C$-comodule structure $\rho_{\mathcal{M}(Y)}:\mathcal{M}(Y)\longrightarrow\mathcal{M}(Y)\otimes C$ on $\mathcal{M}(Y)$ for each $Y\in Ob(\mathcal{D})$. Then, $\mathcal{M}$ is said to be an entwined module over $(\mathcal{D},C,\psi)$ if the following compatibility condition holds: $\rho_{\mathcal{M}(Y)}(\mathcal{M}(f)(m))=\big{(}{\mathcal{M}(f)(m)}\big{)}_{0}% \otimes\big{(}{\mathcal{M}(f)(m)}\big{)}_{1}=\mathcal{M}(f_{\psi})(m_{0})% \otimes{m_{1}}^{\psi}$ for every $f\in Hom_{\mathcal{D}}(Y,X)$ and $m\in\mathcal{M}(X).$ We denote by ${\mathscr{M}(\psi)}_{\mathcal{D}}^{C}$ the category whose objects are entwined modules over $(\mathcal{D},C,\psi)$ and whose morphisms are given by $Hom_{\mathscr{M}(\psi)_{\mathcal{D}}^{C}}(\mathcal{M},\mathcal{N}):=\{\eta\in Hom% _{Mod\text{-}\mathcal{D}}(\mathcal{M},\mathcal{N})\ |\ \eta(X):\mathcal{M}(X)% \longrightarrow\mathcal{N}(X)~{}\text{is $C$-colinear}~{}\forall X\in Ob(% \mathcal{D})\}$
Definition 3.8. Let $C$ and $C^{\prime}$ be two internal categories in $\bm{\mathsf{XMod}}$. A morphism (internal functor) from $C$ to $C^{\prime}$ is a pair of crossed module morphisms $f=\left({{f}_{1}}=\left\langle f_{1}^{A},f_{1}^{B}\right\rangle,{{f}_{0}}=% \left\langle f_{0}^{A},f_{0}^{B}\right\rangle\right):C\to C^{\prime}$ such that ${{f}_{0}}s=s{{f}_{1}}$, ${{f}_{0}}t=t{{f}_{1}}$, ${{f}_{1}}\varepsilon=\varepsilon{{f}_{0}}$ and ${{f}_{1}}m=m\left({{f}_{1}}\times{{f}_{1}}\right)$.
Definition 2.7. A topological crossed module $\left(A,B,\alpha\right)$ consist of two topological groups $A$ and $B$, a continuous group homomorphism $\alpha:A\to B$ and a continuous action of $B$ on $A$ such that the conditions of Proposition 2.2 are satisfied.
Definition 2.9. Let $\mathbb{C}$ be a category with pullbacks. Then an internal category $C$ in $\mathbb{C}$ consist of two objects ${{C}_{1}}$ and ${{C}_{0}}$ in $\mathbb{C}$ and four structure morphisms $s,t:{{C}_{1}}\to{{C}_{0}}$, $\varepsilon:{{C}_{0}}\to{{C}_{1}}$ and $m:{{C}_{1}}\,{}_{s}{{\times}_{t}}\,{{C}_{1}}\to{{C}_{1}}$, where ${{C}_{1}}\,{}_{s}{{\times}_{t}}\,{{C}_{1}}$ is the pullback of $s$ and $t$, such that the following conditions hold: (i) $s\varepsilon=t\varepsilon={{1}_{{{C}_{0}}}}$; (ii) $sm=s{{\pi}_{2}}$, $tm=t{{\pi}_{1}}$ ; (iii) $m\left({{1}_{{{C}_{1}}}}\times m\right)=m\left(m\times{{1}_{{{C}_{1}}}}\right)$ and (iv) $m\left(\varepsilon s{{,1}_{{{C}_{1}}}}\right)=m\left({{1}_{{{C}_{1}}}},% \varepsilon t\right)={{1}_{{{C}_{1}}}}$.
Definition 2.4. [21, 22] Let $\left(A,B,\alpha\right)$ and $\left(S,T,\sigma\right)$ be two crossed modules. Then $\left(S,T,\sigma\right)$ is called a subcrossed module of $\left(A,B,\alpha\right)$ if $S\leq A$, $T\leq B$, $\sigma$ is the restriction of $\alpha$ to $S$ and the action of $T$ on $S$ is the induced action from that of $B$ on $A$.
Definition 2.1. Let $A$ and $B$ two groups and let $B$ acts on $A$ on the left. Then a group homomorphism $\alpha:A\to B$ is called a crossed module if ${{1}_{A}}\times\alpha\colon A\rtimes A\rightarrow A\rtimes B$ and $\alpha\times{{1}_{B}}\colon A\rtimes B\rightarrow B\rtimes B$ are group homomorphisms[24].
Definition 3.9. [7] A crossed square over groups consists of four morphisms of groups $\lambda:L\to M$, ${\lambda}^{\prime}:L\to N$, $\mu:M\to P$ and $\nu:N\to P$, such that $\nu{\lambda}^{\prime}=\mu\lambda$ together with actions of the group $P$ on $L$, $M$, $N$ on the left, conventionally, (and hence actions of $M$ on $L$ and $N$ via $\mu$ and of $N$ on $L$ and $M$ via $\nu$) and a function $h:M\times N\to L$. These are subject to the following axioms: (i) $\lambda$, ${\lambda}^{\prime}$ are $P$-equivariant and $\mu$, $\nu$ and $\kappa=\mu\lambda$ are crossed modules, (ii) $\lambda h(m,n)=m+n\cdot(-m)$, ${\lambda}^{\prime}h(m,n)=m\cdot n-n$, (iii) $h(\lambda(l),n)=l+n\cdot(-l)$, $h(m,{\lambda}^{\prime}(l))=m\cdot l-l$, (iv) $h(m+{m}^{\prime},n)=m\cdot h({m}^{\prime},n)+h(m,n)$, $h(m,n+{n}^{\prime})=h(m,n)+n\cdot h(m,{n}^{\prime})$, (v) $h(p\cdot m,p\cdot n)=p\cdot h(m,n)$ for all $l\in L$, $m,{m}^{\prime}\in M$, $n,{n}^{\prime}\in N$ and $p\in P$.
Definition 2.8. Let $\left(A,B,\alpha\right)$, $\left(M,P,\mu\right)$ and $\left(C,D,\gamma\right)$ be three crossed modules and $f=\left\langle{{f}_{A}},{{f}_{B}}\right\rangle:\left(A,B,\alpha\right)\to\left% (M,P,\mu\right)$ and $g=\left\langle{{g}_{C}},{{g}_{D}}\right\rangle:\left(C,D,\gamma\right)\to\left% (M,P,\mu\right)$ be two crossed module morphisms. Then the pullback crossed module of $f$ and $g$ is $\left(A{}_{{{f}_{A}}}{{\times}_{{{g}_{C}}}}C,B{}_{{{f}_{B}}}{{\times}_{{{g}_{D% }}}}D,\alpha\times\gamma\right)$ where the action of $B{}_{{{f}_{B}}}{{\times}_{{{g}_{D}}}}D$ on $A{}_{{{f}_{A}}}{{\times}_{{{g}_{C}}}}C$ is given by $\left(b,d\right)\cdot\left(a,c\right)=\left(b\cdot a,d\cdot c\right)$ for all $\left(b,d\right)\in B{}_{{{f}_{B}}}{{\times}_{{{g}_{D}}}}D$ and $\left(a,c\right)\in A{}_{{{f}_{A}}}{{\times}_{{{g}_{C}}}}C$.
Definition 2.5. [21, 22] Let $\left(A,B,\alpha\right)$ be a crossed module and $\left(S,T,\sigma\right)$ a subcrossed module of $\left(A,B,\alpha\right)$. Then $\left(S,T,\sigma\right)$ is called a normal subcrossed module or an ideal of $\left(A,B,\alpha\right)$ if (i) $T\triangleleft B$, (ii) $b\cdot s\in S$ for all $b\in B$, $s\in S$ and (iii) $t\cdot a-a\in S$ for all $t\in T$,$a\in A$.
Definition 6.1. Let $\mathcal{V}$ be a coaisle of a homotopically smashing t-structure (so, in particular, $\mathcal{V}$ can be a definable coaisle) in the derived category $\operatorname*{\mathbf{D}}(R)$ of a valuation domain $R$. Denote $\mathcal{V}_{n}=\{M\in\operatorname*{Mod-R}\mid M[-n]\in\mathcal{V}\}$, and let $\mathcal{K}_{n}=\{\operatorname*{\mathfrak{p}}\in\operatorname*{Spec}(R)\mid% \kappa(\operatorname*{\mathfrak{p}})\in\mathcal{V}_{n}\}$ for each $n\in\mathbb{Z}$. Inspired by [Ba07],[Ba15], we define the two following assignments on prime ideals in the same way as in Section 4.5: $\varphi_{n}(\operatorname*{\mathfrak{p}})=\inf\{\operatorname*{\mathfrak{q}}% \in\operatorname*{Spec}(R)\mid R_{\operatorname*{\mathfrak{q}}}/\operatorname*% {\mathfrak{p}}\in\mathcal{V}_{n}\},$ $\psi_{n}(\operatorname*{\mathfrak{p}})=\sup\{\operatorname*{\mathfrak{q}}\in% \operatorname*{Spec}(R)\mid R_{\varphi_{n}(\operatorname*{\mathfrak{p}})}/% \operatorname*{\mathfrak{q}}\in\mathcal{V}_{n}\}.$ Finally, we define for each $n\in\mathbb{Z}$ a set $\mathcal{X}_{n}=\{[\varphi_{n}(\operatorname*{\mathfrak{p}}),\psi_{n}(% \operatorname*{\mathfrak{p}})]\mid\operatorname*{\mathfrak{p}}\in\mathcal{K}_{% n}\}$ of formal intervals in $\operatorname*{Spec}(R)$.
